-<tr id='C-05-manufactured-outrage-001'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-05-manufactured-outrage-001'>C-05-manufactured-outrage-001</a></td><td>The Jussie Smollett case turned an invented hate-crime story into a national morality play before trial evidence showed he had paid acquaintances to stage the attack.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./05-manufactured-outrage.html">5. Manufactured outrage and narrative laundering</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 288)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>Smollett showed how fast a useful hate-crime story can outrun verification</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>smollett, hate-crime-hoax, media</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>1</td><td><a href="https://unherd.com/2021/12/how-jussie-smolletts-hoax-unravelled/" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://unherd.com/2021/12/how-jussie-smolletts-hoax-unravelled/</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-05-manufactured-outrage-002'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-05-manufactured-outrage-002'>C-05-manufactured-outrage-002</a></td><td>The Covington Catholic case showed the same thing in miniature: a misleading clip, immediate racist framing, and much quieter correction after fuller footage showed the students had been misrepresented.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./05-manufactured-outrage.html">5. Manufactured outrage and narrative laundering</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 294)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>Covington Catholic became a template for clip-based moral indictment</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>covington, media, outrage</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>1</td><td><a href="https://reason.com/2019/01/21/covington-catholic-high-school-media/" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://reason.com/2019/01/21/covington-catholic-high-school-media/</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-05-manufactured-outrage-003'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-05-manufactured-outrage-003'>C-05-manufactured-outrage-003</a></td><td>The &quot;Hands up, don&#x27;t shoot&quot; narrative outlived the DOJ findings that witness accounts behind it were unreliable and unsupported by the physical record.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./05-manufactured-outrage.html">5. Manufactured outrage and narrative laundering</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 300)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>Ferguson showed how a slogan can survive its evidentiary collapse</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>ferguson, doj, narrative-laundering</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>1</td><td><a href="https://www.stlpr.org/government-politics-issues/2015-03-24/why-did-the-justice-department-conclude-that-hands-up-dont-shoot-was-a-myth" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.stlpr.org/government-politics-issues/2015-03-24/why-did-the-justice-department-conclude-that-hands-up-dont-shoot-was-a-myth</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-05-manufactured-outrage-004'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-05-manufactured-outrage-004'>C-05-manufactured-outrage-004</a></td><td>The Bubba Wallace &quot;noose&quot; story became international news even though the FBI concluded it was a garage-door pull rope that had been in the stall since the prior year and was not directed at Wallace.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./05-manufactured-outrage.html">5. Manufactured outrage and narrative laundering</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 306)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>Bubba Wallace showed how symbolic-racism stories get global reach before basic context</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>nascar, bubba-wallace, media</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>1</td><td><a href="https://www.espn.com/racing/nascar/story/_/id/29354447/fbi-says-rope-had-talladega-garage-last-fall-bubba-wallace-not-victim-hate-crime" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.espn.com/racing/nascar/story/_/id/29354447/fbi-says-rope-had-talladega-garage-last-fall-bubba-wallace-not-victim-hate-crime</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-05-manufactured-outrage-005'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-05-manufactured-outrage-005'>C-05-manufactured-outrage-005</a></td><td>Police said the Atlanta spa shooter blamed the spas for his sex addiction and said the attacks were not racially motivated, yet the anti-Asian-hate framing spread faster and farther than the correction.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./05-manufactured-outrage.html">5. Manufactured outrage and narrative laundering</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 312)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>Atlanta spa coverage locked onto a racial script before the facts supported it</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>atlanta-spa, anti-asian-hate, media</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>1</td><td><a href="https://www.courthousenews.com/atlanta-area-shootings-leave-8-dead-many-of-asian-descent/" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.courthousenews.com/atlanta-area-shootings-leave-8-dead-many-of-asian-descent/</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-05-manufactured-outrage-006'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-05-manufactured-outrage-006'>C-05-manufactured-outrage-006</a></td><td>The Nashville Christian-school attack produced selective omission: reporting highlighted the victims and community response while some outlets downplayed the shooter&#x27;s transgender identity even though that detail would almost certainly have been foregrounded if the ideological roles were reversed.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./05-manufactured-outrage.html">5. Manufactured outrage and narrative laundering</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 318)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>Nashville coverage showed asymmetric identity emphasis</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>nashville, trans, media, asymmetry</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>1</td><td><a href="https://www.christianpost.com/news/cbs-told-staff-not-to-report-christian-school-shooter-was-transgender.html" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.christianpost.com/news/cbs-told-staff-not-to-report-christian-school-shooter-was-transgender.html</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-05-manufactured-outrage-007'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-05-manufactured-outrage-007'>C-05-manufactured-outrage-007</a></td><td>Rolling Stone&#x27;s UVA rape story and the Duke lacrosse case both showed how moral panic, institutional appetite, and media appetite can outrun basic verification and leave innocent targets carrying the social stain long after collapse.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./05-manufactured-outrage.html">5. Manufactured outrage and narrative laundering</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 324)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>UVA and Duke remain two of the cleanest journalistic-moral-panic receipts</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>uva, duke, rape-hoax, media</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>2</td><td><a href="https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/highly-anticipated-review-rolling-stone-campus-rape-story-released" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/highly-anticipated-review-rolling-stone-campus-rape-story-released</a> <a href="https://today.duke.edu/showcase/lacrosseincident/" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://today.duke.edu/showcase/lacrosseincident/</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-05-manufactured-outrage-008'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-05-manufactured-outrage-008'>C-05-manufactured-outrage-008</a></td><td>In Canada, the Toronto hijab-cutting hoax and the residential-school mass-graves story both functioned as high-speed moral weapons before scrutiny caught up.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./05-manufactured-outrage.html">5. Manufactured outrage and narrative laundering</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 331)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>Canadian examples show the same speed-versus-verification failure mode</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>canada, hijab-hoax, residential-schools, media</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>3</td><td><a href="https://www.meforum.org/a-hijabi-hoax-that-fooled-canada" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.meforum.org/a-hijabi-hoax-that-fooled-canada</a> <a href="https://nowtoronto.com/news/hijab-hoax-on-who/" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://nowtoronto.com/news/hijab-hoax-on-who/</a> <a href="https://www.fraserinstitute.org/commentary/no-evidence-of-mass-graves-or-genocide-in-residential-schools" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.fraserinstitute.org/commentary/no-evidence-of-mass-graves-or-genocide-in-residential-schools</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-06-protected-categories-001'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-06-protected-categories-001'>C-06-protected-categories-001</a></td><td>*Meriwether v. Hartop* shows that a public university really did discipline a professor over pronouns before the Sixth Circuit revived his free-speech and free-exercise claims; the case later ended in a reported $400,000 settlement.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./06-protected-categories.html">6. Protected categories, compelled language, and race-explicit preferences</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 351)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>Meriwether turned a pronoun dispute into major constitutional litigation</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>pronouns, universities, free-speech</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>3</td><td><a href="https://www.opn.ca6.uscourts.gov/opinions.pdf/21a0071p-06.pdf" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.opn.ca6.uscourts.gov/opinions.pdf/21a0071p-06.pdf</a> <a href="https://www.fire.org/news/blogs/ronald-kl-collins-first-amendment-news/shawnee-state-university-pays-400k-following" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.fire.org/news/blogs/ronald-kl-collins-first-amendment-news/shawnee-state-university-pays-400k-following</a> <a href="https://adflegal.org/case/meriwether-v-trustees-shawnee-state-university/" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://adflegal.org/case/meriwether-v-trustees-shawnee-state-university/</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-06-protected-categories-002'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-06-protected-categories-002'>C-06-protected-categories-002</a></td><td>*Vlaming v. West Point School Board* shows that a K-12 teacher was fired over pronouns before appellate correction, with a later reported settlement of $575,000.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./06-protected-categories.html">6. Protected categories, compelled language, and race-explicit preferences</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 359)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>Vlaming showed pronoun enforcement could cost a schoolteacher his job</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>pronouns, schools, virginia</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>2</td><td><a href="https://www.courthousenews.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/vlaming-v.-west-point-school-board-supreme-court-of-virginia-opinion.pdf" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.courthousenews.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/vlaming-v.-west-point-school-board-supreme-court-of-virginia-opinion.pdf</a> <a href="https://adflegal.org/article/vlaming-v-west-point-school-board-settlement-details" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://adflegal.org/article/vlaming-v-west-point-school-board-settlement-details</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-06-protected-categories-003'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-06-protected-categories-003'>C-06-protected-categories-003</a></td><td>*Nelson v. Goodberry Restaurant Group* is a clean Canadian workplace receipt: the BC Human Rights Tribunal treated repeated pronoun misuse and gendered nicknames as actionable and ordered damages plus policy changes.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./06-protected-categories.html">6. Protected categories, compelled language, and race-explicit preferences</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 366)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>Nelson shows direct Canadian workplace enforcement tied to pronouns</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>canada, pronouns, tribunal</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>2</td><td><a href="https://www.bchrt.bc.ca/shareddocs/annual_reports/2021-2022.pdf" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.bchrt.bc.ca/shareddocs/annual_reports/2021-2022.pdf</a> <a href="https://www.bchrt.bc.ca/law-library/leading-cases/protected-characteristics/" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.bchrt.bc.ca/law-library/leading-cases/protected-characteristics/</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-06-protected-categories-004'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-06-protected-categories-004'>C-06-protected-categories-004</a></td><td>*Miller v. College of Policing* showed that police recording and warning over gender-critical speech could create a serious chilling effect even without a criminal prosecution.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./06-protected-categories.html">6. Protected categories, compelled language, and race-explicit preferences</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 373)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>Miller showed how non-crime recording can still punish speech</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>uk, police, gender-critical, chilling-effect</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>2</td><td><a href="https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/Miller-v-College-of-Policing-judgment-201221.pdf" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/Miller-v-College-of-Policing-judgment-201221.pdf</a> <a href="https://www.judiciary.uk/judgments/miller-v-the-college-of-policing/" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.judiciary.uk/judgments/miller-v-the-college-of-policing/</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-06-protected-categories-005'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-06-protected-categories-005'>C-06-protected-categories-005</a></td><td>*Forstater v. CGD Europe* remains the cleanest UK receipt that belief in biological sex as immutable can be legally protected, even after a lower tribunal treated the belief as outside protection.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./06-protected-categories.html">6. Protected categories, compelled language, and race-explicit preferences</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 380)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>Forstater forced a legal correction against sex-realism overreach</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>uk, forstater, sex-realism, employment</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>2</td><td><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/60c1cce1d3bf7f4bd9814e39/Maya_Forstater_v_CGD_Europe_and_others_UKEAT0105_20_JOJ.pdf" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/60c1cce1d3bf7f4bd9814e39/Maya_Forstater_v_CGD_Europe_and_others_UKEAT0105_20_JOJ.pdf</a> <a href="https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Forstater-JR-AG.pdf" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Forstater-JR-AG.pdf</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-06-protected-categories-006'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-06-protected-categories-006'>C-06-protected-categories-006</a></td><td>The Restaurant Revitalization Fund used an explicit priority window that pushed white male owners to the back of a limited grant line because of race and sex; the Sixth Circuit said the plaintiffs were likely to succeed.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./06-protected-categories.html">6. Protected categories, compelled language, and race-explicit preferences</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 389)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>Vitolo is a clean receipt of race-and-sex priority in federal relief</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>vitolo, rrf, equal-protection</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>2</td><td><a href="https://www.sba.gov/article/2021/apr/19/sba-announces-official-restaurant-revitalization-fund-application-guidelines" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.sba.gov/article/2021/apr/19/sba-announces-official-restaurant-revitalization-fund-application-guidelines</a> <a href="https://www.opn.ca6.uscourts.gov/opinions.pdf/21a0120p-06.pdf" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.opn.ca6.uscourts.gov/opinions.pdf/21a0120p-06.pdf</a></td></tr>
-<tr id='C-06-protected-categories-007'><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href='./claims.html#C-06-protected-categories-007'>C-06-protected-categories-007</a></td><td>ARP Section 1005 created debt relief for &quot;socially disadvantaged&quot; farmers and ranchers, and courts repeatedly treated the race-based design as unlawful.</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'><a href="./06-protected-categories.html">6. Protected categories, compelled language, and race-explicit preferences</a> <span style='opacity:.7'>(line 396)</span></td><td style='white-space:nowrap'></td><td>ARP Section 1005 reserved a major federal benefit by race</td><td style='white-space:nowrap'>farmers, race, holman-vilsack</td><td style='text-align:right;white-space:nowrap'>3</td><td><a href="https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/COMPS-16472/pdf/COMPS-16472.pdf" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/COMPS-16472/pdf/COMPS-16472.pdf</a> <a href="https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/FR-2021-05-26/pdf/2021-11155.pdf" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/FR-2021-05-26/pdf/2021-11155.pdf</a> <a href="https://www.opn.ca6.uscourts.gov/opinions.pdf/25a0024p-06.pdf" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.opn.ca6.uscourts.gov/opinions.pdf/25a0024p-06.pdf</a></td></tr>
